offered during end-of-life. Rather, Dossa draws attention to an organic form of caring, illustrated through the trajectories of storied lives. In exemplifying more humane aspects of social palliation, this book foregrounds sacred traditions to illustrate their potential to evoke deep-level conversations across socio-political boundaries on what it is like to live and die in the contemporary world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aDeathxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aOlder MuslimsxCarezCanada. 0aOlder MuslimszCanadaxSocial life and customs. 0aOlder immigrantsxCarezCanada. 0aOlder immigrantszCanadaxSocial life and customs. 0aPalliative treatmentxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aTerminal carexSocial aspectszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aCanada.  adying.  alives.  aliving.  amuslim.  apalliation.  asacred.  asocial.  astoried.  atraditions.  awomen.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753180540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487531805423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487531805.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles